                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d924">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/632: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-04-18T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 18, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>119. Tientsin’s 54, April 15, noon, and 55, April 17, 4 p.m.<note n="19"
                        xml:id="d924fn19">Neither printed.</note> Please make an approach to the
                    Japanese Foreign Office in such manner as you may deem appropriate but without
                    mention of the Tientsin Chamber of Commerce and point out emphatically that the
                    long-continued and unlawful interference by Japanese armed forces and their
                    agencies with the movement of American citizens and of American-owned <pb
                        facs="0860" n="852" xml:id="pg_852"/> merchandise at Tientsin has been the
                    subject of repeated conversations between American and Japanese officials but
                    without cessation of such interference. The Department suggests that you say
                    that it seems obvious that further instruction from Tokyo to the Japanese armed
                    forces at Tientsin will be required to effect an improvement in the situation
                    and that you ask that such instruction be sent.</p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo via Peiping. Repeated to Chungking and Tientsin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
